data.title: TV Premiere Dates (2024
data.meta_description: Find a frequently updated calendar of premiere dates for all upcoming new and returning television shows on broadcast, streaming, and cable, plus TV movies and specials and VOD releases.
data.text:
tbd Pachinko - Trailer

Drama: Widely praised when it debuted in 2022, Apple's epic family drama series adapted from Min Jin Lee's novel finally returns for its second season today. Once again, the action takes place in multiple time periods, countries, and languages (Korean, Japanese, and English) as it traces the story of multiple generations of a Korean family throughout the 20th century. New episodes stream weekly through October 11.Apple TV+ tbd Only Murders in the Building - Trailer

Comedy: Picking up following the events of last year's finale, which ended with the murder of Sazz (Jane Lynch), the fourth season of Hulu's hit murder mystery comedy series finds our trio of amateur sleuths/podcasters (played once again by Steve Martin, Martin Short, and Selena Gomez) heading across the country to Los Angeles as they investigate Sazz's death. In Hollywood, they'll also encounter the filming of a movie adaptation of their podcast in which the trio is portrayed by Eugene Levy (as Charles), Zach Galifianakis (as Oliver), and Eva Longoria (as Mabel). Other newcomers this season include Molly Shannon, Melissa McCarthy, Kumail Nanjiani, Richard Kind, and Desmin Borges, while Meryl Streep will return from Season 3. Hulu tbd Kaos Trailer

Comedy/Drama/Fantasy: A new series from The End of the F***g World creator Charlie Covell, KAOS is an irreverent take on the world of Greek mythology. Jeff Goldblum stars as the cruel, paranoid, and neurotic god Zeus, who worries (correctly) that his reign may be coming to an end, while Janet McTeer plays his increasingly independent wife (and sister) Hera, and Stephen Dillane portrays the imprisoned Prometheus, who hatches a plan to take down Zeus. Eight episodes stream today.Netflix tbd Terminator Zero Trailer

Anime: Netflix's latest original anime series is set in Japan in both 2022 and 1997 and takes place in the world of the Terminator movies but features all new characters. (And, with Japan being a gun-free country, they may have an especially tough time battling killing machines from the future.) The series comes from writer Matt Tomlin (The Batman), while the animation comes from the Japanese studio behind Ghost in the Shell. Timothy Olyphant heads the voice cast, which also includes Rosario Dawson, Ann Dowd, Andre Holland, and Sonoya Mizuno. All eight episodes stream today.Netflix tbd English Teacher Trailer

Comedy: Created by and starring Brian Jordan Alvarez, FX's new workplace comedy centers on a high school teacher in Austin. Jonathan Krisel (Portlandia, Baskets) and Paul Simms (What We Do in the Shadows, Atlanta) are producers on the series, which also stars Enrico Colantoni, Sean Patton, Langston Kerman, and Stephanie Koenig. The first two (of eight) episodes air back-to-back tonight and stream tomorrow on Hulu.FX 10p

Hulu (9/3)Fight Night: The Million Dollar Heist Trailer

Drama: A fictionalized retelling of an intriguing true-crime tale adapted from the Will Packer-produced podcast Fight Night, this eight episode miniseries is set in Atlanta in 1970. As a hustler known as Chicken Man (Kevin Hart) hosts a wealthy crowd at a party celebrating Muhammad Ali's return to the ring, a brazen armed robbery takes place. When the cops suspect Chicken Man of masterminding the crime, he must clear his name—changing the future of the Atlanta in the process. An impressive cast also includes Samuel L. Jackson, Don Cheadle, Taraji P. Henson, and Terrence Howard, while Craig Brewer (Hustle & Flow) directs four of the episodes.Peacock tbd The Perfect Couple Trailer

Drama: Adapted from the Elin Hilderbrand novel of the same name, this six-part Netflix original from Jenna Lamia (Good Girls) is set during a busy Fourth of July weekend on Nantucket when a ritzy wedding involving a wealthy family is upended by the discovery of a dead body in the harbor. Nicole Kidman, Liev Schreiber, Dakota Fanning, Eve Hewson, Billy Howle, Omar Epps, Jack Reynor, and Meghann Fahy star. Susanne Bier (The Night Manager) directs the series in its entirety.NetflixUniversal Basic Guys Trailer Animation/Comedy: Originally ordered in 2022 (and already picked up for a second season), the latest entry into Fox's Animation Domination block comes from Adam and Craig Malamut (Sports Friends) and follows two brothers who are out of work after being replaced at the hot dog factory by robots. But there's good news: They qualify for a new basic income program guaranteeing them $3,000 a month with no strings attached. How do they use their free time and money? Probably not well.

*Tonight's episode (followed by Bob's Burgers) begins immediately following NFL coverage live in all time zones.Fox 8p ET*Three Women Trailer

Drama: Originally ordered by Showtime (in 2019!) but later jettisoned in a cost-cutting move, this 10-episode adaptation of the book by Lisa Taddeo stars Shailene Woodley, Betty Gilpin, DeWanda Wise, Blair Underwood, and Gabrielle Creevy. Woodley plays a writer who convinces three "ordinary" women to share their stories about how they radically overhauled their lives in different ways.Starz 10p tbd American Sports Story: Aaron Hernandez Trailer

Drama: The first season of Ryan Murphy's latest FX anthology series offers a fictionalized retelling of the rise and fall of Aaron Hernandez, the one-time NFL star for the New England Patriots who was later convicted of murder and died in prison in 2017. Adapted from the Boston Globe/Wondery podcast Gladiator: Aaron Hernandez and Football Inc., the season stars Josh Andrés Rivera (West Side Story) as Hernandez alongside Patrick Schwarzenegger as Tim Tebow and Norbert Leo Butz as Bill Belichick. The first two (of 10) episodes air tonight and stream tomorrow on Hulu.FX 10p

Hulu (9/18)High Potential

Drama/Comedy: Adapted from a French series called HIP—High Intellectual Potential (which you can find streaming on Hulu), ABC's new detective dramedy stars Kaitlin Olson (It's Always Sunny in Philadelphia) as a single mom who works as a janitor at a police precinct. After she speaks up to help solve a tricky case, the police enlist her as a consultant and team her with a by-the-book (what else?) detective played by Daniel Sunjata. The adaptation comes from Drew Goddard (The Good Place) but no longer has Veronica Mars creator Rob Thomas as showrunner; he was replaced a few months ago by Todd Harthan (The Resident). ABC 10pAgatha All Along Trailer

Comedy/Drama/Sci-fi: In development for three years under at least five different potential titles, this WandaVision spinoff finds Katherine Hahn reprising her Emmy-nominated role as New Jersey witch Agatha Harkness, who seeks to regain her powers after losing them in the prior series. Also starring in this latest MCU series (which comes, like WandaVision before it, from Jac Schaeffer) are Aubrey Plaza, Joe Locke, Sasheer Zamata, Patti LuPone, and Debra Jo Rupp. The first two of nine episodes stream tonight, and Agatha won't be the only WandaVision spinoff: Another centering on Paul Bettany's Vision is due in 2026.Disney+ 9p ET / 6p PT tbd Frasier

Comedy: The revived Kelsey Grammer comedy returns with the first two episodes of its second season today. Guests this season include Peri Gilpin (returning from the original series as Roz)—plus familiar faces from the KACL studio, which Frasier will visit in one episode—along with Patricia Heaton, Amy Sedaris, Yvette Nicole Brown, and Rachel Bloom.Paramount+The Penguin Trailer

Drama: Originally a Max series but now bearing the HBO brand, this long-in-development DC Comics project is a spinoff from Matt Reeves' 2022 film The Batman and returns Colin Farrell as mob boss Oswald Cobblepot, aka The Penguin. Also starring in the eight-episode miniseries, which picks up shortly following the events of the film with Gotham still under water, are Cristin Milioti, Rhenzy Feliz, Shohreh Aghdashloo, Michael Kelly, Carmen Ejogo, and Clancy Brown. The series comes from writer/showrunner Lauren LeFranc (Agents of SHIELD, Chuck)—though Reeves is among the producers—while Craig Zobel (Mare of Easttown) directs the first three episodes. Note that the the next episode will not air until Sunday 9/29 at 9p (the show's regular timeslot moving forward). HBO 9p

MaxA Very Royal Scandal

Drama: The production team behind the recent limited series A Very English Scandal and A Very British Scandal return with a three-part dramatization of the events surrounding an infamous 2019 interview between a scandal-plagued Prince Andrew (Michael Sheen) and journalist Emily Maitlis (Ruth Wilson). If that sounds vaguely familiar, it might be because Netflix already aired a different dramatization of the interview earlier this year (though this new series, made with the input of the real-life Maitlis, will center more on her than on the disgraced prince). All three episodes stream today.Prime Video tbd His Three Daughters Trailer

Drama: Carrie Coon, Natasha Lyonne, and Elizabeth Olsen star as three very different sisters who come together in the final days of their father's life. Azazel Jacobs (French Exit) writes and directs the drama, which received excellent reviews at TIFF in 2023 and which will also receive a limited theatrical release beginning September 6. NetflixMatlock

Drama: Kathy Bates stars in a remake of the 1980s legal drama (you know, the one that starred whatshisname from The Andy Griffith Show). Beau Bridges, Jason Ritter, and Skye P. Marshall also star. Tonight's airing is a special sneak preview of the first episode (which will repeat on Oct. 10); the series returns for its regular run on 10/17 at 9p.CBS 8pRescue HI-Surf Trailer

Drama: It's basically Baywatch in high-definition but minus The Hoff. So ... a wash? It's also set in O'ahu and is produced by John Wells (ER, The West Wing)—so expect an approach that's a bit more serious and slightly more realistic—but the fact that we're not listing the cast means that you probably wouldn't recognize the names. (Either that or we're simply lazy.) Another episode airs tomorrow at 8p, the show's regular Monday timeslot going forward.

* Tonight's episode airs live in all time zones immediately following NFL coverage.Fox 8p ET*Murder in a Small Town Trailer

Drama: Fox's newest drama series centers on a series of arsons in a mid-sized city. (Double-checking our notes ... Oh, we really got that one wrong.) Kristin Kreuk, Rossif Sutherland, James Cromwell, and Stana Katic star in the adaptation of L.R. Wright's Karl Alberg books that follows a big-city police detective relocating to a quiet Pacific Northwest coastal town, where he can't quite escape the need to solve murders. Lots and lots of murders. Tonight's premiere runs 90 minutes; subsequent episodes air Tuesdays at 9p starting 10/1.Fox 8p tbd Nobody Wants This

Comedy: Kristen Bell and Adam Brody play an outspoken, agnostic woman and an unconventional rabbi—you'll have to match the actor to the role on your own—who begin an unlikely romance in a loosely autobiographical comedy series from Erin Foster in her debut as series creator. Also produced by Modern Family's Steven Levitan, the series also counts Succession's Justine Lupe and Veep's Timothy Simons among its regulars. All 10 episodes stream today.Netflix tbd Wolfs Trailer

TV/Action/Comedy/Thriller: Excited about Jon Watts (Spider-Man: Homecoming) directing a comedic action-thriller that re-teams Ocean's 11 stars George Clooney and Brad Pitt? You may want to lower your expectations a bit: Apple recently downgraded the film's Sep. 20 theatrical release from wide to limited and is bringing it to streaming just one week later. However, there's a bit of encouraging news as well: A sequel to the film is already in development.Apple TV+Teacup Trailer

Drama/Horror: Produced by James Wan (Saw, The Conjuring), Peacock's new horror/mystery/sci-fi thriller is loosely based on Robert McCammon's 1988 novel Stinger and finds a group of rural Georgians coping with a mysterious threat—so mysterious that Peacock isn't revealing any details about what it might be. Yvonne Strahovski (The Handmaid's Tale) and Scott Speedman (Underworld) head the cast, while the adaptation comes from writer Ian McCulloch (Yellowstone). Two episodes stream each week through Oct. 31.PeacockDisclaimer Trailer

Drama: Alfonso Cuarón (Roma, Gravity) writes and directs the entirety of a seven-episode psychological thriller adapted from the Renee Knight novel of the same name. Cate Blanchett stars as TV journalist Catherine Ravenscroft, who is alarmed to discover a new novel that appears to feature her as the main character—and discloses a dark secret from her own past. An impressive cast also features Kevin Kline, Sacha Baron Cohen, Lesley Manville, Kodi Smit-McPhee, and Squid Game star Hoyeon Jung, while the cinematography comes from big names Emmanuel Lubezki and Bruno Delbonnel. The first two episodes stream today.Apple TV+Like a Dragon: Yakuza Trailer

Foreign/Drama: Set in both 1995 and 2005, Amazon's new Japanese-language series is a live-action adaptation of Sega's Yakuza (aka Like a Dragon) videogame franchise. Three episodes stream today, while the concluding three arrive on November 1.Prime VideoBefore

Drama: Apple's 10-episode psychological thriller features a cast mostly known for comedy. Created by Sarah Thorp (The Bounty Hunter), Before stars Billy Crystal as Eli, a recently widowed child psychiatrist who encounters a troubled young boy who appears to have a connection to Eli's own past. Judith Light and Rosie Perez also star. The first two episodes stream today.Apple TV+The Day of the Jackal Trailer

Drama: Eddie Redmayne and Lashana Lynch star in an assassin thriller based on Frederick Forsyth's novel, which was previously adapted into a pair of feature films (one great, one not). The 10-episode series (a Peacock and Sky co-production) finds Redmayne playing a killer for hire who draws the attention of Lynch's British intelligence officer, who then pursues him across Europe. Charles Dance, Richard Dormer, and Ursula Corbero also star.Peacock tbd Emilia Perez

Comedy/Musical/Thriller: The third-place (Jury Prize) winner at this year's Cannes—where it was also one of the most talked-about films in competition—this ambitious, genre-blending project from A Prophet director Jacques Audiard is mostly a musical melodrama in which Zoe Saldana plays a lawyer who helps a cartel leader (Karla Sofía Gascón) get out of his business, leaving behind his wife (Selena Gomez) and children, and become the woman he has always dreamed of being. While critics at Cannes certainly found the film messy at times (or even all of the time), some also found it exhilarating, and the female ensemble shared the fest's Best Actress award.NetflixCross Trailer

Drama: The latest adaptation—but first for the small screen—of James Patterson's Alex Cross crime novel series stars Aldis Hodge as the titular forensic psychologist alongside Isaiah Mustafa, Juanita Jennings, and Ryan Eggold. All eight episodes stream today, and a second season has already been greenlit.Prime VideoBack in Action

Action/Comedy: Married former CIA agents played by Jamie Foxx and Cameron Diaz (in her first movie role in a decade) get dragged back into the spy game as Netflix's trouble-plagued production finally arrives on the streaming service. Kyle Chandler, Glenn Close, and Andrew Scott also star for writer-director Seth Gordon (The King of Kong, Baywatch).NetflixLandman

Drama: The latest series from Yellowstone creator Taylor Sheridan is adapted from the Texas Monthly-produced podcast Boomtown and follows a group of blue-collar oil workers and the billionaire executives who employ them in West Texas oil country. Billy Bob Thornton heads a cast that also includes Jon Hamm, Demi Moore, Andy Garcia, Ali Larter, Michael Pena, Michelle Randolph, and Jacob Lofland. The first two (of 10) episodes stream today.Paramount+Interior Chinatown

Drama: Jimmy O. Yang (Silicon Valley) stars as Willis Wu, a an actor playing an unnamed background character on a police procedural who stumbles into a larger real-life story involving a criminal conspiracy in Chinatown and his family's secret history, in an adaptation of the acclaimed best-seller of the same name by Charles Yu. Adapted by Yu himself (the author has extensive TV experience including writing for Lodge 49 and Westworld), the drama also stars Ronny Chieng, Chloe Bennet, and Lisa Gilroy. All 10 episodes, including the Taika Waititi-directed opener, stream today.Hulu tbd Blitz

Drama: Writer-director Steve McQueen's first narrative feature since 2018's Widows is set in England during WWII. When a London mother (Saoirse Ronan) sends her 9-year-old son (newcomer Elliott Heffernan) to live in safety (away from the Blitz) in the countryside, the child becomes determined to find his way back home—an adventure that comes with many perils. Apple TV+Star Wars: Skeleton Crew Trailer

Drama/Sci-fi: A Spielberg-inspired coming-of-age tale set within the Star Wars universe—specifically, after the events of Return of the Jedi and concurrent with The Mandalorian, though prior knowledge of the franchise is not a prerequisite—the long-delayed Skeleton Crew follows four kids who make a mysterious discovery on their home planet and then must find their way back home after getting lost in the galaxy. The series comes from Jon Watts (director of the well-received recent Spider-Man films) and Christopher Ford (who co-wrote Spider-Man: Homecoming) and features an all-star roster of directors including Lee Isaac Chung (Twisters), the Daniels (Everything Everywhere All at Once), David Lowery (The Green Knight), Bryce Dallas Howard (The Mandalorian), and Jake Schreier (the upcoming Thunderbolts*). The adult cast is led by Jude Law and also includes Nick Frost, Tunde Adebimpe, and Kerry Condon. The first of eight episodes streams today.Disney+Win or Lose Trailer

Animation/Family: Pixar's first original television series follows the members of a co-ed middle school softball team in the week before their championship game. Each episode shows the point of view of a different character, including players, parents, coaches, and even an umpire. The series has been in development since 2020 and was originally supposed to debut a year ago, only to receive a last-minute delay. Nevertheless, an early episode received an extremely positive reaction when it screened at the Annecy festival last year. Will Forte heads the voice cast.Disney+
